         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Private ¶ 25/7/85 ¶  ¶ I like to mention to you, dear Mr Dyer, that Ottelia ovalifolia does not grow within 100 miles of Melbourne; and as I have no garden whatever, I cannot observe it in cultivation...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">85.07.25</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Thiselton-Dyer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew Correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-1890, f. 155.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Private</hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annotated in red pencil under 'Private':</seg> Sir JDH.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">25/7/85</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I like to mention to you, dear Mr Dyer, that <name key="Ottelia%20ovalifolia">Ottelia ovalifolia</name> does not grow within 100 miles of Melbourne; and as I have no garden whatever, I cannot observe it in cultivation. You will be therefore now with the growing plant before you in a much better position, to describe the particulars of its dimorphism than I ever had.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See W. Watson (1883) for an account of the plants growing at Kew; however, this does not mention dimorphic flowers. M details them in B86.06.04.</p>
               </note> I was wondering why so nice and remarkable a plant was not at once figured in the bot. Magazine, after all the trouble I took in putting Kew into possession of it, and before it flower[s] elsewhere.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The species was not depicted in the<seg style="font-style: italic; "> Botanical magazine. </seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>An illustration, said to be 'from a drawing made by' M, accompanied B86.06.04.</p>
               </note> Mr Fitzgerald seems with <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">his species</hi>
               </seg> of Orchids fast to drift into Jordanism;<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">'Critical botany … has … been exaggerated by Alexis Jordan and his followers into an impracticable and futile extreme' (B. Jackson (1881), p. xxxviii).</p>
               </note> see his <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">numerous</hi>
               </seg> new <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">species</hi>
               </seg> of <name key="Prasophyllum">Prasophyllum</name> even from the long-trodden ground in N.S.W. He spoils his work by the ill differentiation of the species and his want of true appreciation of the specific limits, the faulty etymology e.g. <name key="Dendrobium%20falcirostrum">Dendrobium falcirostrum</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">D. falcorostrum</seg>
                     <seg style="">? (R. Fitzgerald (1876)).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <name key="Sarcochilus%20rubicentrum">Sarcochilus rubicentrum</name>,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">S. rubricentrum</seg>
                     <seg style="">? </seg>(R. Fitzgerald (1880)).</p>
               </note> which more-over is the well known here much cultivated S. Hartmanni[!]<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M described <seg style="font-style: italic; ">S. hartmanni</seg> in B74.10.01, p. 248.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I saved him from making of the N.S.W. <name key="Adenochilus">Adenochilus</name> a new genus; he does not know of Blume's <name key="Pedilonum">Pedilonum</name>, and establishes after the reduction of that again a new genus <name key="Coelandrium">Coelandrium</name>!<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Coelandria</seg>? <seg style="">(R. Fitzgerald (</seg>1875-94), vol. 1 part 7, plate [2]).</p>
               </note> A Gentleman here, who is a good judge, call his illustrations, excellent as they are in other respects, "hazy" and certainly there is a want of sharpness of expression, which the darkness of the paper makes worse. The coloring is often poor, He is sulky with me, his first "Maitre", for not adopting <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">all</hi>
               </seg> his species downright for my Census,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B82.13.08 and subsequent additions.</p>
               </note> and he <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">stands alone</hi>
               </seg> in not preserving any dried specimens either for himself or others.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">or others . . . Mueller <seg style="font-style: italic; ">written in left margin, f 155 front.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I don't believe in the validity of his <name key="Dendrobium%20Phalaenopsis">Dendrobium Phalaenopsis</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">I don't ... Phalaenopsis <seg style="font-style: italic; ">written in central margin, f 155 back.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
